<p>
  gym memberships are the second-highest category of forgotten auto-renewals in the uk — second only to car insurance. and unlike insurance, there's no legal requirement for providers to notify you before renewal.
</p>

<h3>the minimum term expiry trap</h3>

<p>
  most gym contracts in the uk run on 12-month minimum terms. you sign up in january when motivation is high, pay £25–40 a month, and by march you've stopped going. but the contract ticks on. come december, you've paid £300–480 for a gym you visited twelve times.
</p>

<p>
  the real kicker: after the 12-month minimum, the contract often rolls over to a monthly rolling contract — at the same price. the gym has no incentive to tell you. they're perfectly happy for you to keep paying while not using the facilities. some gyms see 40–60% of their revenue from members who visit fewer than once a month.
</p>

<h3>cancellation notice periods: the hidden lock-in</h3>

<p>
  most uk gyms require 30 days' notice to cancel, even on a monthly rolling contract. that means you can't just cancel today — you're committing to one more payment. and if you miss the direct debit date by one day, the next month's payment goes through before your cancellation takes effect.
</p>

<p>
  some chains — particularly boutique studios and premium clubs — require cancellation in writing, by post, or in person. these friction points are designed. every extra step reduces the cancellation rate by approximately 5%.
</p>

<h3>freezing vs cancelling: what you should know</h3>

<p>
  most gyms offer a "freeze" option, charging £5–10/month to pause your membership instead of cancelling. this sounds reasonable until you do the maths: £10/month for 6 months is £60 — to not use a gym. and when the freeze ends, the full payment resumes automatically.
</p>

<p>
  the better option for most people: cancel outright and rejoin when you're ready. rejoining costs nothing, and you often get a new-member discount that's better than your old rate.
</p>
